# Frontend Bilingual Copy

All user-facing text in the landing and checkout apps must be bilingual (English and Arabic) and centralized for easy editing.

## Copy Location

- **All copy lives in** `packages/i18n/messages/`:
  - `en.json` — English translations
  - `ar.json` — Arabic translations

Edit these files to change any user-facing text across both apps. Do **not** hardcode copy in components.

## Rules

1. **Never hardcode user-facing text** in TSX/TS files. Use the `t()` or `get()` functions from `useTranslations()`.
2. **Every new string** must have an entry in both `en.json` and `ar.json` under the appropriate section (e.g. `landing`, `onboard`, `checkout`, `common`).
3. **Match the vibe** — English translations should capture the same casual, friendly, direct tone as the Arabic (Egyptian dialect).
4. **Use nested keys** for organization, e.g. `onboard.step2.businessName`, `checkout.step1.paymentMethod`.
5. **For interpolated values** (e.g. `{sellerName}`), use the `t(key, { varName: value })` pattern.
6. **For arrays** (testimonials, features, steps), use `get("section.items")` to retrieve the full array.

## Usage

```tsx
import { useTranslations } from "@/lib/locale-provider";

function MyComponent() {
  const { t, get } = useTranslations();
  return (
    <>
      <h1>{t("landing.hero.headline")}</h1>
      <p>{t("checkout.step3.successSubtitle", { sellerName })}</p>
      {get("landing.features.items")?.map((item, i) => (
        <div key={i}>{item.title}</div>
      ))}
    </>
  );
}
```

## Language Switcher

Both apps include a `LanguageSwitcher` component. Locale is persisted in a cookie and applies `dir` (rtl/ltr) and `lang` (ar/en) to the document.
